				\begin{document}$\mathcal{O}( N_{\mathrm{PV}} )$\end{document} denotes the correction for additional energy from multiple proton-proton interactions depending on the number of primary vertices (NPV).

In the following, the calibrated calorimeter jet transverse momentum will be denoted as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{jet}}$\end{document}, and the jet pseudorapidity as η.

Proton-proton collisions at a centre-of-mass energy of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\sqrt{s} = 7~ \mathrm{TeV} $\end{document}, recorded from March to October 2010 are analysed. Only data with a fully functioning calorimeter and inner detector are used. The data set corresponds to an integrated luminosity of 38 pb−1. Due to different data quality requirements the integrated luminosity can differ for the various selections used in the in situ technique analyses.

Different triggers are used to select the data samples, in order to be maximally efficient over the entire jet pT-range of interest. The dijet sample is selected using the hardware-based calorimeter jet triggers [30, 85], which are fully efficient for jets with \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{jet}} > 60~ \mathrm{GeV} $\end{document}. For lower \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{jet}}$\end{document} a trigger based on the minimum bias trigger scintillators is used.

The multijet sample uses either the inclusive jet trigger or a trigger that requires at least two, three or more jets with pT>10 GeV at the EM scale. These triggers are fully efficient for jets with \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{jet}} > 80~ \mathrm{GeV} $\end{document}.

Each event is required to have a primary hard scattering vertex. A primary vertex is required to have at least five tracks \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$(N_{\rm pp}^{\rm tracks})$\end{document} with a transverse momentum of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{track}} > 150~ \mathrm{MeV} $\end{document}. The primary vertex associated to the event of interest (hard scattering vertex) is the one with the highest associated transverse track momentum squared, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\sum( p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\rm track})^{2}$\end{document}, used in the vertex fit where the sum runs over all tracks used in the vertex fit. This renders the contribution from fake vertices due to beam backgrounds to be negligible.

In data and Monte Carlo simulation jets are reconstructed using the anti-kt algorithm [25] with distance parameters R=0.4 or R=0.6 using the FastJet software [86, 87]. The four-momentum recombination scheme is used. For jet finding rapidity y is used, while jet corrections and performance studies use often pseudorapidity η. The jet pT reconstruction threshold is \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{jet}} > 7~ \mathrm{GeV} $\end{document}.

Tracks with \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\rm track}>0.5~ \mathrm{GeV} {}$\end{document} and |η|<2.5 are selected. They are required to have at least one (six) hit(s) in the Pixel (SCT) detector. The transverse (d0) and longitudinal (z0) impact parameters of the tracks measured with respect to the primary vertex are also required to be |d0|<1.5 mm and |z0sinθ|<1.5 mm, respectively.

The track jets must have at least two constituent tracks and a total transverse momentum of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p^{\text{track jet}}_{\mathrm{T}} >3~ \mathrm{GeV} $\end{document}. Since the tracking system has a coverage up to |η|=2.5, the performance studies of calorimeter jets is carried out in the range |η|<1.9 for R=0.6 and |η|<2.1 for R=0.4.

Two types of calorimeter noise are addressed: 
Sporadic noise bursts in the hadronic endcap calorimeter (HEC), where a single noisy calorimeter cell contributes almost all of the jet energy. Jets reconstructed from these problematic cells are characterised by a large energy fraction in the HEC calorimeter (fHEC) as well as a large fraction of the energy in calorimeter cells with poor signal shape quality7 (fHECquality). Due to the capacitive coupling between channels, the neighbouring calorimeter cells with little genuine energy will have an apparent negative energy (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$E_{\rm neg}$\end{document}).
Rare coherent noise in the electromagnetic calorimeter. Similarly, fake jets arising from this source are characterised by a large electromagnetic energy fraction (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$f_{\rm EM}$\end{document}),8 and a large fraction of energy in EM calorimeter cells with poor signal shape quality (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$f_{\rm quality}$\end{document}).

Cosmic rays or non-collision backgrounds can induce events where the jet candidates are not in-time with the beam collision. A cut on the jet time (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$t_{\rm jet}$\end{document}) is applied to reject these backgrounds. The jet time is reconstructed from the energy deposition in the calorimeter by weighting the reconstructed time of calorimeter cells forming the jet with the square of the cell energy. The calorimeter time is defined with respect to the event time recorded by the trigger.

A cut on the \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$f_{\rm EM}$\end{document} is applied to make sure that the jet has some energy deposited in the calorimeter layer closest to the interaction region as expected for a jet originating from the nominal interaction point.

Since a real jet is expected to have tracks, the fEM cut is applied together with a cut on the minimal jet charged fraction (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$f_{\rm ch}$\end{document}), defined as the ratio of the scalar sum of the pT of the tracks associated to the jet divided by the jet pT, for jets within the tracking acceptance.

A cut on the maximum energy fraction in any single calorimeter layer (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$f_{\rm max}$\end{document}) is applied to further reject non-collision background.

Two quality selections are provided: 
A loose selection is designed with an efficiency above 99 %, that can be used in most of the ATLAS physics analyses.
A medium selection is designed for analyses that select jets at high transverse momentum, such as for jet cross-section measurements [1]. A tight quality selection has been developed for the measurement of the jet quality selection efficiency described in Sect. 7.2, but is not used in physics analyses, since the medium jet quality selection is sufficient for removing fake jets. The quality selection criteria used to identify and reject fake jets are listed in Table 1. Table 1
