The traditional approach for η-intercalibration with dijet events is to use a fixed central region of the calorimeters as the reference region. The relative calorimeter response to jets in other calorimeter regions is then quantified by the pT balance between the reference jet and the probe jet, exploiting the fact that these jets are expected to have equal pT due to transverse momentum conservation. The pT balance can be characterised by the asymmetry \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\mathcal{A}$\end{document}, defined as 
12\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \mathcal{A} = \frac{ p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{probe}} - p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{ref}} }{ p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{avg}} }, $$\end{document} with \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{avg}} = ( p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{probe}} + p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{ref}} )/2$\end{document}. The reference region is chosen as the central region of the barrel: |η|<0.8. If both jets fall into the reference region, each jet is used, in turn, as the reference jet. As a consequence, the average asymmetry in the reference region will be zero by construction.

The asymmetry is then used to measure an η-intercalibration factor c for the probe jet, or its response relative to the reference jet 1/c, using the relation 
13\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \frac{ p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{probe}} }{ p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{ref}} } =\frac{2+ \mathcal{A} }{2- \mathcal{A} } =1/c. $$\end{document}

The asymmetry distribution is calculated in bins of jet ηdet and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{avg}} $\end{document}: The bins are labeled i for each probe jet ηdet and k for each \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{avg}} $\end{document}-bin. Intercalibration factors are calculated for each bin according to Eq. (13): 
14\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ c_{ik}=\frac{2- \langle \mathcal{A} _{ik} \rangle}{2+ \langle \mathcal{A} _{ik} \rangle}, $$\end{document} where the \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\langle \mathcal{A} _{ik} \rangle $\end{document} is the mean value of the asymmetry distribution in each bin. The uncertainty on \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\langle \mathcal{A} _{ik} \rangle$\end{document} is taken to be the \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\text{RMS/}\sqrt{N}$\end{document} of each distribution, where N is the number of events per bin.

A disadvantage with the method outlined above is that all events are required to have a jet in the central reference region. This results in a significant loss of event statistics, especially in the forward region, where the dijet cross section drops steeply as the rapidity interval between the jets increases. In order to use the full event statistics, the default method can be extended by replacing the “probe” and “reference” jets by “left” and “right” jets defined as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\eta^{\rm left}<\eta^{\rm right}$\end{document}. Equations (12) and (13) then become: 
15\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \everymath{\displaystyle} \begin{array}{@{}l} \mathcal{A} = \frac{ p_{\mathrm {T}} ^{\mathrm{left}} - p_{\mathrm {T}} ^{\mathrm{right}} }{ p_{\mathrm {T}} ^{\mathrm{avg}} } \quad \mathrm{and} \\\noalign{\vspace{8pt}} \mathcal{R}_{l r}= \frac{ p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm {left}} }{ p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{right}} }= \frac{c^{\rm right}}{c^{\rm left}}= \frac{2+ \mathcal{A} }{2- \mathcal{A} }, \end{array} $$\end{document} where the term \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\mathcal{R}$\end{document} denotes the ratio of the responses, and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$c^{\rm left}$\end{document} and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$c^{\rm right}$\end{document} are the η-intercalibration factors for the left and right jets, respectively.

