Several variables can be used sequentially to achieve the optimal resolution. This procedure requires that the correction for a given variable xi (Ci) is calculated using jets to which the correction for the previous variable xi−1 (Ci−1) has already been applied. The jet transverse momentum after correction number i is given by: 
36\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{i} = C^i(x_i) \times p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{i-1} = C^i(x_i) \times C^{i-1}(x_{i-1}) \times p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{i-2} = \cdots $$\end{document}

The longitudinal structure of the jet34 is characterised by the fractional energy deposited in the different layers of the calorimeters before any jet calibration is applied (“layer fractions”): 
37\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ f_{\rm layer} = \frac{E_ \mathrm{EM} ^{\rm layer}}{E_ \mathrm{EM} ^{\rm jet}}, $$\end{document} where \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$E_{ \mathrm{EM} }^{\rm jet}$\end{document} is the jet energy at the EM scale and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$E_{ \mathrm{EM} }^{\rm layer}$\end{document} the energy deposited in the layer of interest, also defined at the EM scale. The transverse jet structure can be characterised by the jet width defined as: 
38\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \mathrm{width}= \frac{\sum_{i} p^i_{\rm T} \Delta R_{i,{\rm jet}}}{\sum_{i} p^i_{\rm T}}, $$\end{document} where the sums are over the jet constituents (i) and pT is the transverse constituent momentum. \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\Delta R_{i,{\rm jet}}$\end{document} is the distance in η×ϕ-space between the jet constituents and the jet axis. In the following study topo-clusters are used as jet constituents.

The jet whose response dependence on the layer fractions or width is studied, is referred to as the probe jet, while the other is referred to as the reference jet. The average transverse momentum of the probe and the reference jet is defined as 
39\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\rm avg} = \bigl( p_{\mathrm {T}} ^{\rm probe}+ p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\rm ref}\bigr)/2. $$\end{document} Since the choice of the reference jet and the probe jet is arbitrary, events are always used twice, inverting the roles of reference and probe.

The GS corrections are measured through the asymmetry variable defined as: 
40\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ A(x) = \frac{ p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\rm probe}(x) - p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\rm ref}}{ p_{\mathrm {T}} ^{\rm avg}(x)}, $$\end{document} where x is any of the properties used in the GS calibration (see Table 13). Both \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\rm probe}$\end{document} and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\rm ref}$\end{document} depend on x, but in a given event the value of x of the probe jet is different from that of the reference jet. For this reason the dependence on x is explicitly written in Eq. (40) only for the probe jet.

The probe and the reference jet transverse momenta are defined with the same calibration. When computing the correction factor Ci, they are both corrected up to the (i−1)th correction (see Sect. 11.1). The mean response as a function of x is given by: 
41\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \bigl\langle R(x) \bigr\rangle= \biggl\langle\frac{ p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\rm probe}}{ p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\rm ref}} \biggr\rangle \simeq\frac{2 + \langle A(x) \rangle}{2 - \langle A(x) \rangle}. $$\end{document} For more details see also discussion in Sect. 9.6.1.

The measurement of the response through the asymmetry defined in Eq. (40) assumes that the asymmetry for truth jets is zero. This is true on average (inclusive in x), but not when computed in bins of x. The measured asymmetry A(x) is therefore a mixture of detector effects and imbalance at the level of the generated particles. In order to remove the effect of imbalance at the level of generated particles, a new asymmetry is defined: 
42\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ A'(x) = A(x) - A_{\rm true}(x), $$\end{document} where A(x) is given by Eq. (40) and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$A_{\rm true}(x)$\end{document} is: 
43\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ A_{\rm true}(x) = \frac{p_{{\rm T},{\rm truth}}^{\rm probe}(x)-p_{{\rm T}, {\rm truth}}^{\rm ref}}{p_{{\rm T},{\rm truth}}^{\rm avg}(x)}, $$\end{document} where \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{{\rm T},{\rm truth}}^{\rm avg}(x) = (p_{{\rm T},{\rm truth}}^{\rm probe}(x)+p_{{\rm T},{\rm truth}}^{\rm ref})/2$\end{document} with \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{{\rm T},{\rm truth}}^{\rm probe}(x)$\end{document} and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{{\rm T},{\rm truth}}^{\rm ref}$\end{document} being the probe and reference jets transverse momenta, respectively. The variable \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$A_{\rm true}(x)$\end{document} denotes the true asymmetry. The variable x in Eq. (42) is that of the reconstructed jet matched to the truth jet. Matching is done using the same criterion as for the EM+JES calibration (see Sect. 8.3). When using A′(x) instead of A(x) in Eq. (41), the effects of imbalance at the level of generated particles are removed and the resulting response depends only on detector effects. Accounting for the truth jet imbalance is particularly important for the corrections that depend on the energy in the presampler and the jet width.

