A tag-and-probe technique is used as described in the following steps: 
Only track jets with pT>5 GeV and |η|<1.9 are considered.
The track jet with the highest pT in the event is defined as the reference object.
The reference object is required to have pT>15 GeV.39
The reference track jet is matched to a calorimeter jet with \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{jet}} > 7~ \mathrm{GeV} $\end{document}, if \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\Delta R ({\rm tag}, \text{calo jet}) < 0.6$\end{document}.40
The probe track jet must be back-to-back to the reference jet in ϕ with |Δϕ|≥2.8 radian.
Events with additional track jets within |Δϕ|≥2.8 radian are rejected.
The calorimeter reconstruction efficiency with respect to track jets is then defined as the fraction of probe track jets matched to a calorimeter jet using \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\Delta R({\rm probe}, \text{calo jet}) < R$\end{document} (with R=0.4 or R=0.6) with respect to all probe track jets.

Figures 72b–d show the measured calorimeter reconstruction efficiency with respect to track jets as a function of the calorimeter jet transverse momentum for anti-kt jets with R=0.6 calibrated with the EM+JES, GCW+JES, and LCW+JES calibration schemes.41 The reconstruction efficiency reaches a plateau close to 100 % at a jet transverse calorimeter momentum of about 25 GeV. The matching efficiency in data (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
