				\begin{document}$20 \leq p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{jet}} < 250~ \mathrm{GeV} $\end{document} the expected difference in the calorimeter response uncertainty of identified b-jets with respect to the one of inclusive jets is less than 0.5 %. It is assumed that this uncertainty extends up to |η|<2.5.

For each effect listed above the b-jet response uncertainty is evaluated from the ratio between the response of b-jets in the Monte Carlo samples with systematic variations to the nominal Pythia MC10 b-jet sample. The deviation from unity of this ratio is taken as uncertainty: 
61\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {\rm Uncertainty} = 1 - \biggl( \frac{ \mathcal{R} ^{ b \text{-jet}}_{\rm variation}}{ \mathcal{R} ^{ b \text{-jet}}_{\rm nominal}} \biggr). $$\end{document}

