fn.p:
The ATLAS coordinate system is a right-handed system with the x-axis pointing to the centre of the LHC ring and the y-axis pointing upwards. The polar angle θ is measured with respect to the LHC beam-line. The azimuthal angle ϕ is measured with respect to the x-axis. The pseudorapidity η is an approximation for rapidity y in the high energy limit, and it is related to the polar angle θ as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\eta= -\ln\tan\frac{\theta}{2} $\end{document}. The rapidity is defined as y=0.5×ln[(E+pz)/(E−pz)], where E denotes the energy and pz is the component of the momentum along the beam direction. Transverse momentum and energy are defined as pT=p×sinθ and ET=E×sinθ, respectively.

With ΔR<0.6 for jets with R=0.6 and ΔR<0.4 for jets with R=0.4, where \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\Delta R = \sqrt{(\Delta\eta)^{2} + (\Delta\phi)^{2}} $\end{document}.

The missing transverse momentum (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}${E}_{\mathrm{T}}^{\mathrm{miss}}$\end{document}) significance is defined as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}${E}_{\mathrm{T}}^{\mathrm{miss}} /\sqrt{\sum E_{\mathrm{T}}}$\end{document}, where \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\sum E_{\rm T}$\end{document} is the scalar sum of the transverse energies of all energy deposits in the calorimeter.

\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$X(c_{ik})=K ( N_{\rm bins}^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^{N_{\rm bins}} c_{ik} - 1 )^{2}$\end{document} is defined with K being a constant and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$N_{\rm bins}$\end{document} being the number of η-bins (number of indices i). This term prevents the minimisation from choosing the trivial solution: all cik equal to zero. The value of the constant K does not impact the solution as long as it is sufficiently large (K≈106).

This cut is not applied, if it would be below the jet pT reconstruction threshold of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{jet}} = 7~ \mathrm{GeV} $\end{document}. If in this case a sub-leading jet with \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{jet}} \ge7~ \mathrm{GeV} $\end{document} is present, the event is rejected.

Such (small) inconsistencies are seen in the comparison of the γ-jet and track jet results in one \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{jet}}$\end{document} bin.

Technically, the efficiency is first measured as a function of the track jet pT. Using the known relation between the average track jet and the average calorimeter jet pT, the track jet pT is then converted to the calorimeter jet \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$p_{\mathrm{T}} ^{\mathrm{jet}}$\end{document}.

The \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$n_{\rm trk}$\end{document} and jet width templates are dealt with independently, and the results of their estimates of flavour fraction are not combined.
